         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0329">
               <p>A native of <placeName>Stepney, Middlesex</placeName>, as early as <date
                     when="1742">1742</date> Butts was looking after <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s book-keeping at the
                  Foundery in <placeName>London</placeName>, when he was still &apos;on trial&apos;
                  there as a member of a single men&apos;s band. On <date when="1746-05-19">May 19,
                     1746</date> he married <persName>Hannah Witham</persName> (<date from="1720"
                     to="1762">1720–62</date>), with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> officiating. By <date when="1754-12">Dec. 1754</date> Butts
                  appears to have been replaced as <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName>&apos;s book steward by <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2270.xml"/>Robert Windsor</persName>, and set up on his
                  own as a music publisher, building on the success of <hi rend="italic">Harmonia
                     Sacra</hi> (<date when="1753">1753</date>). See Karen Mulhallen (ed.), <hi
                     rend="italic">Blake in our Time</hi> (Toronto: University of Toronto Press,
                     <date when="2010">2010</date>), 131–64.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
